Parkinson's Disease Classification with KNN¶

by Group 28 (Michael DeMarco, Philip Zhang, Chris Cai, Yuichi Ito)

Figure 1 A screengrab from Praat, the acoustic analysis software used in collecting the data set

Introduction¶

Background¶

Parkinson’s disease (PD) is a degenerative disorder of the central nervous system (CNS) which severely impacts motor control. Parkinson’s has neither a cure nor a known cause. Speech, however, is widely known to play a significant role in the detection of PD. According to Sakar1 , vocal disorder exists in 90% of patients at an early stage.

[1] Here's the link to the original data set, and corresponding paper. Note that the paper used the data before a study with a similar goal but with very different predictor variables than the ones we select (to begin with) here.

Question¶

To what extent can we use elements of speech sounds to predict whether or not a patient has Parkinson’s disease?

Data set¶

Our data set is from UCI’s Machine Learning repository. This data set contains numerous variables in speech sounds gathered by Sakar using the Praat acoustic analysis software. Each participant in the study was asked to repeat their pronunciations of the /a/ phoneme three times; each entry is thus associated with an ID parameter ranging from 0 to 251. We chose to focus on the following six predictor parameters:

Speech Sound Variable Name Variable Name in Data Set Description
Pitch Period Entropy (PPE)⁠ TBD measures the impaired control of someone’s pitch
Detrended Fluctuation Analysis (DFA)⁠ TBD a measure of the ‘noisiness’ of speech waves
Recurrence Period Density Entropy (RPDE)⁠ TBD repetitiveness of speech waves
Jitter TBD a measure of frequency instability
Shimmer TBD a measure of amplitude instability
Fundamental Frequency TBD someone’s pitch (calculated from the inverse of the mean period)⁠
Figure 2 Table describing each of the predictor's used in the original analysis

There’s a lot of complicated math associated with each of these parameters (including Fourier transforms, dense equations, etc.) so the interested reader is encouraged to reference Sakar directly.

Preliminary exploratory data analysis in R¶

We'll now conduct a preliminary exploration of the data using R, to getter a better sense of what we'll be working with.

# Averages the values of each subject's three trials so that each subject is represented by one row
project_data <- baseline_data %>%
                group_by(id) %>%
                summarize(PPE = mean(PPE),
                     DFA = mean(DFA),
                     RPDE = mean(RPDE),
                     meanPeriodPulses = mean(meanPeriodPulses),
                     locPctJitter = mean(locPctJitter),
                     locShimmer = mean(locShimmer),
                     # meanAutoCorrHarmonicity = mean(meanAutoCorrHarmonicity),--legacy from project proposal
                     class = mean(class)) %>%
                     mutate(class = as.factor(class)) %>%
                     mutate(has_pd = (class == 1))

# plot_pairs

plot_pairs_by_class <- training_set %>%
                       ggpairs(.,
                               legend = 9,
                               columns = 2:8, 
                               mapping = ggplot2::aes(colour=has_pd), 
                               lower = list(continuous = wrap("smooth", alpha = 0.3, size=0.1)),
                               title = "PD speech predictor variable correlations by class") +
                       theme(legend.position = "bottom")
# plot_pairs_by_class

The following two plots were created using GGPairs. The first, in black, provides some detail about the distribution and correlation between the pairs of our six predictor variables in a toned down view. Three of our predictors, DFA, RPDE, and meanPeriodPulses take on a much wider range of values than PPE, jitter, and shimmer. Many of our variables also exhibit somewhat positive correlations on the scatterplot, or have an entirely fuzzy distribution. For example, compare the plots in the PPE column to those in the RPDE column. This likely comes as a result of the spread of the predictors.

In [21]:
options(repr.plot.width=10,repr.plot.height=10, repr.plot.pointsize=20)

plot_pairs

With this understanding, we can use a second plot, grouped and colored by has_pd to help us anticipate what the impact of these predictors will be. We can see that for every individual distribution, there is a marked difference between the red and blue groupings, which bodes well for our analysis. On average, the healthy patients (i.e., has_pd == FALSE) fall on the lower end of the spectrum for our predictors, apart from PPE, where they exhibit higher values on average. Though we won’t be able to visualize our final model directly (as it is in six dimensions), we can predict from those plots that the new patients which fall on the lower end for most of these distributions should be healthy. This also makes intuitive sense; Parkinson’s is a degenerative disease for the muscles, so patients would likely have higher, more rapid change in various speech variables, due to tremors.
